CHAPTER 11\par
11:1 Mine are no strange discourses nor perverse\par
questionings, but having been a disciple of Apostles I\par
come forward as a teacher of the Gentiles, ministering\par
worthily to them, as they present themselves disciples\par
of the truth, the lessons which have been handed down.\par
11:2 For who that has been rightly taught and has\par
entered into friendship with the Word does not seek to\par
learn distinctly the lessons revealed openly by the\par
Word to the disciples; to whom the Word appeared and\par
declared them, speaking plainly, not perceived by the\par
unbelieving, but relating them to disciples who being\par
reckoned faithful by Him were taught the mysteries of\par
the Father?\par
11:3 For which cause He sent forth the Word, that He\par
might appear unto the world, Who being dishonoured by\par
the people, and preached by the Apostles, was believed\par
in by the Gentiles.\par
11:4 This Word, Who was from the beginning, Who\par
appeared as new and yet was proved to be old, and is\par
engendered always young in the hearts of saints,\par
11:5 He, I say, Who is eternal, Who to-day was\par
accounted a Son, through Whom the Church is enriched\par
and grace is unfolded and multiplied among the saints,\par
grace which confers understanding, which reveals\par
mysteries, which announces seasons, which rejoices\par
over the faithful, which is bestowed upon those who\par
seek her, even those by whom the pledges of faith are\par
not broken, nor the boundaries of the fathers\par
overstepped.\par
11:6 Whereupon the fear of the law is sung, and the\par
grace of the prophets is recognised, and the faith of\par
the gospels is established, and the tradition of the\par
apostles is preserved, and the joy of the Church\par
exults.\par
11:7 If thou grieve not this grace, thou shalt\par
understand the discourses which the Word holds by the\par
mouth of those whom He desires when He wishes.\par
11:8 For in all things, that by the will of the\par
commanding Word we were moved to utter with much\par
pains, we become sharers with you, through love of the\par
things revealed unto us.\par
\par
CHAPTER 12\par
12:1 Confronted with these truths and listening to\par
them with attention, ye shall know how much God\par
bestoweth on those that love (Him) rightly, who become\par
a Paradise of delight, a tree bearing all manner of\par
fruits and flourishing, growing up in themselves and\par
adorned with various fruits.\par
12:2 For in this garden a tree of knowledge and a\par
tree of life hath been planted; yet the tree of\par
knowledge does not kill, but disobedience kills;\par
12:3 for the scriptures state clearly how God from\par
the beginning planted a tree [of knowledge and a tree]\par
of life in the midst of Paradise, revealing life\par
through knowledge; and because our first parents used\par
it not genuinely they were made naked by the deceit of\par
the serpent.\par
12:4 For neither is there life without knowledge,\par
nor sound knowledge without true life; therefore the\par
one (tree) is planted near the other.\par
12:5 Discerning the force of this and blaming the\par
knowledge which is exercised apart from the truth of\par
the injunction which leads to life, the apostle says,\par
_Knowledge puffeth up, but charity edifieth._\par
12:6 For the man who supposes that he knows anything\par
without the true knowledge which is testified by the\par
life, is ignorant, he is deceived by the serpent,\par
because he loved not life; whereas he who with fear\par
recognises and desires life plants in hope expecting\par
fruit.\par
12:7 Let your heart be knowledge, and your life true\par
reason, duly comprehended.\par
12:8 Whereof if thou bear the tree and pluck the\par
fruit, thou shalt ever gather the harvest which God\par
looks for, which serpent toucheth not, nor deceit\par
infecteth, neither is Eve corrupted, but is believed\par
on as a virgin,\par
12:9 and salvation is set forth, and the apostles\par
are filled with understanding, and the passover of the\par
Lord goes forward, and the congregations are gathered\par
together, and [all things] are arranged in order, and\par
as He teacheth the saints the Word is gladdened,\par
through Whom the Father is glorified, to Whom be glory\par
for ever and ever. Amen.\par
